Rating: 4
Loved this! Great flavors. I'm always looking for new ways for fish since we eat alot of it down here in SoFlo. I did substitute local grouper for the sea bass. I used about 1 3/4 lb for 4 people, cut the grouper into 2" (or so) thick slices. 2 other modifications: This only needs to bake for 20-25 minutes and I drizzled the vinaigrette over the fish too. Delicious!

Rating: 4
I grew up in Hawaii, eating fish regularly so am really picky and so is my family. This was fantastic. My brother who usually just eats and grunts raised his eyebrows and said this is restaurant quality (whatever that means, he meant it as a compliment). 23 year old nephew was studying an hour or so after dinner and looked up saying "I keep thinking of that food!". The only thing I did differently was to double the vinaigrette as another reader suggested and drizzle some on top of the fish at the end.

Rating: 3
Because sea bass is not only expensive but also on its way out of its existence on earth (due to over-fishing) I substituted Grouper instead which I would recommend, especially to those of you who think sea bass is a little on the rich side. I made this for a potluck and it was gone 3 minutes. The mustard is an "interesting" touch, I love it, but some may not be so keen. Definitely going to reappear in the future

Rating: 4
This is THE most awesome recipe for seabass ever! I've made this a couple of times now and I always get rave reviews from company. Also, this is a really great recipe if you are having a dinner party for many people. Most of the work can be done ahead and all that is left is the plating of the food... A great first course is the leek, potato and scallop soup (also on this site) and for dessert flourless chocolate cake (from Trader Joe's) with port and or coffee.. yum. The only other thing I would note is that there is a definite difference between making this with fresh seabass versus frozen. I prefer the fresh even though it is expensive.. if i hadn't had the fresh first I probably would have been fine with the frozen but since I have, I'll pay the extra and use fresh....

